# Strict mounted-component control paths

## Goal

Make `ds.get(control_path)` resolve one explicit control path relative to the
current mounted component. Remove the global descendant-ID selector before the
first release so selection cannot silently depend on an unrelated descendant
or on propagated `subviews` entries.

The refactor is complete when every selection traverses direct native child
relationships from the mounted component root, every repository and consumer
call site uses an explicit path, and both missing controls and invalid trees
produce path-oriented diagnostics.

## Decisions

- `ds.get(control_path)` has one selection mode; it never falls back to a
  global descendant search.
- A control path is relative to the mounted component root. The mounted root
  is not a path segment and remains available through `ds.root()`.
- `/` separates path segments. Every segment is the exact `view_id` of one
  direct child of the control resolved by the preceding segment.
- Resolution inspects only the ordered direct children in
  `ipairs(parent.subviews)`. It does not use propagated named entries such as
  `parent.subviews.some_id`.
- Anonymous controls are real hierarchy boundaries and cannot be skipped. A
  branch that authors need to address must give every control on its path a
  usable `view_id`.
- Empty segments, leading or trailing separators, `.`, `..`, and `view_id`
  values containing `/` are invalid.
- A parent control must not contain multiple direct children with the same
  `view_id`. DwarfSpec reports such a tree as invalid instead of selecting one.
- The same `view_id` may appear beneath different parents because their full
  control paths remain distinct.
- Subjects retain their canonical control path so interaction, stale-subject,
  and failure diagnostics identify the complete selection.
- Dynamic child changes become selectable only after the existing successful
  render refresh updates the mount-owned path index.

## Public contract

- [ ] Rename public parameters, documentation, and diagnostics from `view_id`
  to `control_path` where they describe a `ds.get()` selection.
- [ ] Specify that `ds.get('window')` selects a direct child of the mounted
  root named `window`.
- [ ] Specify that `ds.get('window/subpanel/mycontrol01')` traverses three
  direct-child relationships.
- [ ] Specify that `ds.get('mycontrol01')` fails when that control exists only
  beneath `window/subpanel`.
- [ ] Keep `ds.root()` as the only selector for the mounted component itself.
- [ ] Define malformed-path errors independently from missing-control errors.
- [ ] Define the duplicate-direct-child condition as an invalid mounted tree.
- [ ] Define whether the subject exposes `control_path` publicly and remove or
  redefine its current selection-oriented `view_id` field accordingly.

## Mount-context implementation

- [ ] Remove the flat `views_by_id` index and `duplicate_view_ids` tracking.
- [ ] Replace `find_view(view_id)` with a control-path resolver whose name and
  parameters reflect the strict path contract.
- [ ] Parse and validate the complete path before attempting tree traversal.
- [ ] Traverse numeric `subviews` entries only, comparing each direct child's
  own `view_id` with the current segment.
- [ ] Do not read propagated string-keyed `subviews` entries during selection
  or indexing.
- [ ] Detect duplicate direct-child IDs while refreshing the mounted tree and
  report the parent control path and duplicated ID.
- [ ] Permit identical IDs beneath different parent paths.
- [ ] Decide between a canonical `control_path -> view` index and direct
  traversal, then use the same hierarchy rules for lookup and diagnostics.
- [ ] Rebuild all path and ownership state after successful renders so dynamic
  additions, removals, and moves are reflected atomically.
- [ ] Clear all path-index and subject-selection state during mount cleanup.
- [ ] Preserve weak native-view ownership and stale-subject rejection.
- [ ] Confirm the private widget host is excluded for ordinary widgets and
  overlays, while a mounted complete screen remains the path root.

## Subjects and diagnostics

- [ ] Store the canonical control path on every subject returned by `ds.get`.
- [ ] Keep root-subject identity distinct from a child control path.
- [ ] Record the requested and canonical control path in command context.
- [ ] Update fluent-command failures to report the complete control path.
- [ ] Update stale-subject and removed-subtree failures to report the complete
  control path and mount identity.
- [ ] Report the resolved prefix and failing segment for a missing control.
- [ ] Include the current parent's sorted direct-child IDs in missing-segment
  diagnostics, with an explicit bound for large child lists.
- [ ] Update retained mount diagnostics and JSON-compatible evidence without
  discarding fields needed by existing report consumers.
- [ ] Ensure diagnostic tree capture continues to show the native hierarchy
  used by path resolution.

## Repository and consumer migration

- [ ] Inventory every `ds.get(...)` call in DwarfSpec source, unit tests, live
  automation tests, examples, and documentation.
- [ ] Replace every nested DwarfSpec selection with its complete path.
- [ ] Update ordinary-widget automation coverage, including selections below
  `nested_panel`.
- [ ] Update overlay-widget and complete-screen automation selections to use
  paths relative to their mounted component roots.
- [ ] Inventory every `ds.get(...)` call in DwarfUI and other checked-out
  consumers that will ship against the initial DwarfSpec release.
- [ ] Migrate every known consumer call site; do not add a compatibility
  fallback or deprecation alias for global descendant lookup.
- [ ] Search active code again for single-segment selectors that refer to
  controls below the mounted root and resolve every match explicitly.

## Unit coverage

- [ ] Resolve a direct child with a one-segment path.
- [ ] Resolve a deeply nested child with a multi-segment path.
- [ ] Prove that a leaf-only selector cannot find a nested descendant.
- [ ] Prove that a named intermediate control cannot be skipped.
- [ ] Prove that an anonymous intermediate control cannot be skipped.
- [ ] Prove that the mounted root's own `view_id` is not consumed as a segment.
- [ ] Resolve identical leaf IDs beneath two different parent paths.
- [ ] Reject duplicate IDs among one parent's direct children.
- [ ] Reject empty paths, empty segments, leading and trailing `/`, `.`, `..`,
  and IDs containing `/`.
- [ ] Report the resolved prefix, failing segment, and available children when
  an intermediate or final segment is missing.
- [ ] Refresh paths after dynamic addition, removal, and reparenting.
- [ ] Reject a subject after its selected subtree is removed.
- [ ] Preserve subject validity when an unrelated subtree changes.
- [ ] Cover path metadata in interaction, render, stale-subject, and retained
  mount diagnostics.
- [ ] Remove unit expectations for global descendant and global duplicate-ID
  behavior.

## Live DFHack coverage

- [ ] Add or migrate an ordinary-widget example that interacts through a
  multi-segment path.
- [ ] Prove two controls with the same leaf ID under different parents can be
  selected and interacted with independently.
- [ ] Prove a dynamic descendant becomes selectable by its full path after the
  render that adds it.
- [ ] Exercise strict relative paths for an isolated overlay component.
- [ ] Exercise strict relative paths for a complete screen component.
- [ ] Confirm missing-path failure evidence contains the mounted tree and the
  precise unresolved segment.
- [ ] Confirm each live run finishes with cleanup verification and no retained
  subjects, screens, or pointer state.

## Documentation and packaging

- [ ] Update `README.md` examples to use explicit control paths.
- [ ] Update `docs/writing-tests.md` with the path grammar, root semantics,
  anonymous-boundary rule, and duplicate-parent invariant.
- [ ] Update `docs/architecture.md` to describe the path index and direct-child
  traversal instead of propagated global ID indexing.
- [ ] Update command/reference documentation and the unreleased changelog.
- [ ] Update package-contract tests if subject or diagnostic fields change.
- [ ] Confirm the rock contains every changed runtime and automation-support
  module and no obsolete selector implementation.

## Validation

- [ ] Run the complete DwarfSpec Busted unit suite.
- [ ] Run Lua syntax and formatting checks with the supported system Lua.
- [ ] Parse the changed Lua files with DFHack's embedded Lua runtime.
- [ ] Run the DwarfSpec live automation suite locally through
  `tools/Run-AutomationTests.ps1`; do not add it to GitHub CI.
- [ ] Run migrated DwarfUI unit and live automation coverage against the same
  packaged DwarfSpec artifact.
- [ ] Run rockspec lint, pack the rock, inspect its manifest, and install it
  into an empty LuaRocks tree.
- [ ] Run `git diff --check` and confirm the worktree contains only intended
  refactor changes.

## Completion criteria

- [ ] `ds.get()` has no global descendant-search code path.
- [ ] Every successful selection is reproducible by walking direct children
  from the mounted component root.
- [ ] Every known DwarfSpec and consumer selector uses the strict path contract.
- [ ] Duplicate direct-child IDs and malformed paths fail deterministically.
- [ ] Unit tests pass without DFHack or the game.
- [ ] Local live tests prove strict paths against the DFHack host.
- [ ] Documentation presents only the strict control-path behavior intended for
  the initial release.
